  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>micro-influencer</strong> is a content creator with 10,000–100,000 followers on platforms like Instagram, TikTok, YouTube, or LinkedIn. They sit between nano-influencers (under 10K) and macro-influencers (100K–1M), and their defining quality is genuine audience trust — followers treat their recommendations like advice from a knowledgeable peer, not a billboard.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Follower range</div>
            <div class="tms-value">10K – 100K</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">CRO / Influencer</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Avg. engagement</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3–5% (Instagram)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Cost per post</div>
            <div class="tms-value">$100 – $500</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">77% of brands now prefer micro-influencers over celebrities. The reason is straightforward: smaller audiences follow micro-influencers because they genuinely care what that person thinks — and that trust transfers to the brands they mention.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a micro-influencer?</h2>
        <p>A micro-influencer is a digital creator whose follower count sits between 10,000 and 100,000. The number alone doesn't define them — plenty of accounts in that range have hollow, disengaged audiences. What separates genuine micro-influencers is <strong>audience depth</strong>: their followers are concentrated around a specific topic (skincare, small-batch coffee, B2B SaaS, local food), and they engage at rates most large accounts can't match.</p>
        <p>The category emerged as brands discovered that reach without relevance produces poor ROI. A fashion influencer with 2 million followers and 0.4% engagement delivers fewer qualified impressions than a niche skincare creator with 40,000 followers and 4.8% engagement — especially when your product is a serum.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">2024 benchmark</div>
          <p>Micro-influencers average a <strong>3.86% engagement rate on Instagram</strong> compared to 1.21% for mega-influencers (1M+ followers). Source: Influencer Marketing Hub 2024 Benchmark Report.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why micro-influencers matter for conversion</h2>
        <p>The micro-influencer advantage compounds across four dimensions:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Higher engagement rate.</strong> 3–5% on Instagram versus 1–2.5% for macro accounts. Every post surfaces to a larger share of followers organically.</li>
          <li><strong>Lower cost per impression.</strong> At $100–500 per post versus $5,000–20,000 for macro creators, you can run 10 parallel partnerships for the price of one macro deal — and diversify risk.</li>
          <li><strong>Niche authority.</strong> A Portland food blogger carries real credibility with Portland diners. A skincare chemist carries real credibility with ingredient-conscious buyers. Celebrities carry surface credibility with everyone — which is credibility with no one in particular.</li>
          <li><strong>Authentic content.</strong> Micro-influencers produce content that looks and sounds like their regular output, not a paid spot. Audiences trained to skip ads don't skip it.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How micro-influencer marketing actually works</h2>
        <p>A typical micro-influencer campaign moves through four phases:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Discovery.</strong> Find candidates via hashtag search on Instagram and TikTok, competitor tag audits, influencer marketplaces like Aspire or Grin, or by identifying local creators in your category.</li>
          <li><strong>Vetting.</strong> Check engagement rate (target above 3%), follower authenticity via tools like HypeAuditor, content quality, and audience geography/demographics.</li>
          <li><strong>Campaign structure.</strong> Define deliverables (1 Reel + 3 Stories, for example), provide a creative brief with guardrails but not a script, and agree on usage rights if you plan to repurpose content in ads.</li>
          <li><strong>Compensation.</strong> Options include flat fees, product-only deals, affiliate commissions, or hybrid arrangements. Below 25,000 followers, product-only is common. Above 50,000, expect cash.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="types">Types of micro-influencers</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Focus</th><th>Best for</th><th>Engagement profile</th></tr>
            </thead>
