              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real micro-influencer campaign examples</h2>
        <p>Three campaigns that show what good micro-influencer execution looks like — and one that shows what poor targeting costs you.</p>

        <h3>1. Portland coffee shop — local micro-influencer cluster</h3>
        <p>A specialty coffee shop partnered with 5 Portland food bloggers at $200 per post. Each had between 12,000 and 35,000 local followers. Result: 32% increase in foot traffic over the campaign month, tracked via promo code redemptions. Total spend: $1,000.</p>

        <h3>2. SaaS company — LinkedIn micro-influencer reviews</h3>
        <p>A B2B SaaS tool activated 10 LinkedIn marketers with 15,000–80,000 followers, paying $500 per honest review post. Results: 1,400 trial signups at a blended cost of $35 per trial — well below their $150 CAC target from paid search.</p>

        <h3>3. DTC skincare — creator-led product education</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Campaign setup</span><br>
          Platform: <span class="uf-new">Instagram Reels + Stories</span><br>
          Creators: <span class="uf-new">8 skincare micro-influencers, 20K–60K followers each</span><br>
          Brief: <span class="uf-new">Explain ingredient [X] in your own words, show application</span><br>
          Result: <span class="uf-status">3x saves and shares vs. brand's standard posts</span>
        </div>

        <h3>4. The mismatch case — what not to do</h3>
        <p>An accounting firm paid a fashion influencer $800 to mention their tax service to a college-age audience. Engagement: 0.4%. Clicks: 3. The audience followed her for outfit ideas, not tax planning. Follower count matched, audience intent did not.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Micro-influencer vs. macro-influencer — which to use</h2>
        <p>Both have a place. The question is whether you need reach or resonance.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Choose micro when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Budget is under $5,000 per campaign</li>
              <li>Your product requires explanation or trust</li>
              <li>You're targeting a specific niche or location</li>
              <li>You want to test multiple audience segments</li>
              <li>You need authentic content for organic feed</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Choose macro when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Brand awareness at scale is the goal</li>
              <li>Product is mass-market (food, apparel, tech)</li>
              <li>You need celebrity association for brand lift</li>
              <li>Budget supports $5,000–20,000 per post</li>
              <li>You're launching and need rapid reach</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 micro-influencer best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Lead with engagement rate, not follower count.</strong> A creator with 18,000 followers and 5.2% engagement outperforms one with 90,000 followers and 1.1% engagement on almost every conversion metric.</li>
          <li><strong>Verify authentic followers before signing.</strong> Use HypeAuditor, Modash, or Upfluence to check for suspicious follower spikes, bot patterns, or engagement pod activity.</li>
          <li><strong>Give creative freedom within a brief.</strong> Provide the core message, key product claim, and any required disclosures. Let the creator write the hook and narrative in their own voice.</li>
          <li><strong>Build long-term partnerships over one-off posts.</strong> A creator who mentions your product three times in six months builds compounding credibility — not a single impression that fades in 48 hours.</li>
          <li><strong>Track with unique codes or UTM links.</strong> Every creator gets a unique promo code or UTM parameter so you can attribute sales and calculate true ROI per creator, not just campaign-level averages.</li>
          <li><strong>Pair influencer content with organic SEO.</strong> Influencer content drives awareness and social proof. SEO captures the search intent it generates — "brand review," "product comparison," "best [category]." Both channels feed each other.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — skipping the audience-fit check</div>
          <p>Follower count and engagement rate don't tell you if the audience matches your buyer. Always request an audience demographics screenshot (age, gender, top locations) before signing. A creator with 45,000 followers in the wrong country or wrong age bracket costs the same but delivers zero qualified impressions.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common micro-influencer mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Chasing follower count over engagement rate</strong> — the metric that predicts conversion is engagement, not reach.</li>
          <li><strong>Over-scripting the content</strong> — when creator posts sound like ad copy, audiences disengage. Brief, don't script.</li>
          <li><strong>One-and-done partnerships</strong> — single posts rarely move the needle. Frequency builds trust.</li>
          <li><strong>No attribution tracking</strong> — without promo codes or UTM links, you can't tell which creator drove sales.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping the disclosure requirement</strong> — FTC rules require #ad or #sponsored labeling. Non-disclosure exposes your brand to regulatory risk and erodes audience trust when discovered.</li>
          <li><strong>Paying for vanity metrics</strong> — likes and comments are soft signals. Track link clicks, promo redemptions, and trial signups instead.</li>
        </ul>

